McDonald's Nutrition Facts EDA

Brief Info on the dataset

  • This dataset provides a nutrition analysis of every menu item on the US McDonald's menu, including breakfast, beef burgers etc

  • From the data we can analyze -

    • How much calories the average McDonald's value meal contains?
    • How much beverages, like soda or coffee, contribute to the overall caloric intake?
    • If ordering grilled chicken instead of crispy increases a sandwich's nutritional value?
    • If ordering egg whites instead of whole eggs increases nutritional value?
    • The least number of items could you order from the menu to meet one day's nutritional requirements?
    • And More..

Making the Serving size column normal
In[11]:
# working on the serving size column to convert everything to grams (g)

import re

# Define the regular expression pattern for extracting values in brackets
pattern = re.compile(r'\((.*?)\)')

# Apply the pattern to the 'Serving size' column and extract the values
mac['Serving Size'] = mac['Serving Size'].apply(lambda x: pattern.findall(x)[0] if pattern.findall(x) else x)

# function to extract and convert values
def serve(size):
    if ' g' in size:
        return float(size.replace(' g','')) # return value in g
    elif 'fl oz' in size: 
        x, y = size.split(' fl oz')
        return round(float(float(x) * 29.574)) # 1 fl oz == 29.574 ml == 29.574g
    elif ' ml' in size:
        return float(size.replace(' ml','')) # 1ml == 1g
In[12]:
# apply and rename column
mac['Serving Size'] = mac['Serving Size'].apply(serve)
mac = mac.rename(columns = {'Serving Size': 'Serving Size (g)'})

What are the Food Items with Maximum Nutrient Values for Each Category?

In[21]:
# Pick the columns needed from the dataframe mac

mac2 = mac[['Category','Item','Serving Size (g)','Calories', 'Calories from Fat',             
            'Total Fat', 'Saturated Fat', 'Trans Fat', 'Cholesterol','Sodium',              
            'Carbohydrates', 'Dietary Fiber', 'Sugars', 'Protein']]

# Get the maximum value for each numerical column and group by 'Category','Item', 'Serving Size'
def getmax(col):
    x = mac2.groupby(['Category','Item', 'Serving Size (g)'])[col].idxmax() # gets the index where the columns are maximum
    
    # outputs the 'Category','Item' and 'Serving Size' where the numerical column values are max 
    return mac2.loc[x, ['Category','Item', 'Serving Size (g)', col]].sort_values(by=col, ascending=False).iloc[0]
    # iloc[0] brings only the 1st row with max value

# Plot the graph
fig, ax = plt.subplots()


data = []   # create an empty variable to sort and hold the maximum values in ascending order
for col in mac2.columns[3:]:
    # Gets the maximum values for each column and puts it in max_val variable
    max_val = getmax(col) 
    # put the column name, the max value, and the Item name for the max value into data variable
    data.append((col, max_val[col], max_val['Item'])) 

data.sort(key=lambda x: x[1])  # Sort data in ascending order of first maximum values

# Define a color palette
colors = sns.color_palette('crest', len(data))

for i, (col, val, item) in enumerate(data):
    # creates a horizontal bar chart
    ax.barh(i, val, label=col,color=colors[i]) 
    # adds the Item name in front of the bars with spacing of val+10 and font size of 10
    ax.text(val+10, i, item, ha='left', va='center', fontsize=10) 

ax.set_yticks(range(len(data))) # Gets all values of columns to be plotted
ax.set_yticklabels([x[0] for x in data], fontsize=10) # gets the column names for the values in data to be plotted
ax.set_ylabel('Nutrition Categories') # label the y axis
ax.set_xlabel('Amount') # label the x axis
ax.set_title('Food Items with Maximum Value for Each Category') # give the graph a title


plt.show()

Observation -

* Chicken Mcnuggets (40 Piece) is the Food item with the highest amount of nutrients
* It is high in Sodium, Calories, Calories from fat, Total fat and Protein

Which Item of Food product has the highest and lowest level of Sodium and how does the serving size relate to the amount of nutrient?

Create Function to get max and min values for any category

In[26]:
# Pick the needed columns from the dataframe

mac2 = mac[['Category','Item','Serving Size (g)','Calories', 'Calories from Fat', 'Total Fat', 'Saturated Fat', 'Trans Fat', 
            'Cholesterol','Sodium','Carbohydrates', 'Dietary Fiber', 'Sugars', 'Protein']]

# Get the maximum value for each numerical column and group by 'Category','Item', 'Serving Size'
def getmax(col):
    x = mac2.groupby(['Category', 'Item', 'Serving Size (g)'])[col].idxmax() # gets the index where the columns are maximum
    
    # outputs the 'Category','Item' and 'Serving Size' where the numerical column values are max 
    return mac2.loc[x, ['Category', 'Item', 'Serving Size (g)', col]].sort_values(by=col, ascending=False).head().sort_values(by=col,ascending = True).reset_index()
    # .head(5) brings out first 5 maximum values

for col in mac2.columns[3:]: # loops through and gets the max values for each column
    getmax(col) # calls the function
    

#-------------------------Get Minimum------------------------------------------------#

    
# Get the minimum value for each numerical column and group by 'Category','Item', 'Serving Size'
def getmin(col):
    x = mac2.groupby(['Category', 'Item', 'Serving Size (g)'])[col].idxmin() # gets the index where the columns are minimum
    
    # outputs the 'Category','Item' and 'Serving Size' where the numerical column values are max 
    return mac2.loc[x, ['Category', 'Item', 'Serving Size (g)', col]].sort_values(by=col, ascending=True).head().sort_values(by=col,ascending = False).reset_index()
    # .head(5) brings out first 5 minimum values

for col in mac2.columns[3:]: # loops through and gets the min values for each column
    getmin(col) # calls the function

Interactive Graph that changes when the appropriate items are selected

* To create outputs and visuals which can be easily used to sort through the data in the dataset.
* Can select any category and get items from that category and visualize according to the nutrient amount.
* Can compare different food items nutrients and % daily value.
* Can comapare nutrients amount per category.

### create a function to get unique values from columnns, sort them and pass to a list ###

# creates variable called 'All'
All = 'All'

# create the function
def unique_sorted(array):
    """sorts, gets unique values and pass to list"""
    unique = array.sort_values().unique().tolist() # sorts, gets unique values and pass to list
    unique.insert(0, All) # inserts sorted unique list to All variable
    return unique # return the unique values

# Use ipywidgets to create the drop downs
import ipywidgets as widgets
In[56]:
# Main

### create a function using ipywidgets dropdowns to plot bar graphs depending on the selected item ###

nutrients_output = widgets.Output() # ouput of the widgets to be displayed 
nutrients_plot = widgets.Output() # ouput of the selected graph to be displayed


#-------------------------------create variables to be passed into dropdown widgets----------------------------#

sel_cat = widgets.Dropdown(options=unique_sorted(mac['Category']), description = 'Category')  # uses uniques_sorted funct. to get unique category
sel_item = widgets.Dropdown(options=unique_sorted(mac['Item']), description = 'Items') # uses uniques_sorted funct. to get unique items
sel_size = widgets.IntSlider(min = 0, max = 1000, step = 20, description = 'Serving Size', value = 1000) # creates a slider that filters output depending serving size
sel_nutrient = widgets.Dropdown(options = nutrient, description = 'Sort Nutrients')  # sorts and outputs nutrients for items in descending order
sel_value = widgets.Dropdown(options = daily_value, description = 'Sort % Daily Value')  # sorts and outputs % daily values for items in descending order

sel_plot = widgets.Dropdown(options = mix, description='Plot') # passes the columns to plot as options


#--------------------create function to get unique items when a category is selected----------------------#

def get_items_in_category(category):
    
    if category == 'All':
        # if category == All, return all unique items
        return unique_sorted(mac['Item']) 
    else:          
        # elif a unique category is selected, return unique items for category
        return unique_sorted(mac[mac['Category'] == category]['Item']) 
        
#--------------------create function to sort items when a nutrient is selected----------------------#
        
def sort_by(df,value):
    if value in df.columns:
        return df.sort_values(by = value, ascending = False)
    
#----------------create function to get dropdown values and filter outputs as values are changed--------------#        
       
def category_filtering(category, item, size, nutrient, value, plot):
    nutrients_output.clear_output() # clears the ouput of the selected items when a new one is selected
    nutrients_plot.clear_output() # clears the ouput of the selected graph when a new one is selected

    #------------------------Filter For selected category---------------------------#
    
    if category == 'All':
        category_filter = mac # if category = All, category filter = mac dataframe
        item_options = get_items_in_category('All') # item_options updates to unique items for that category    
    else:
        category_filter = mac[mac['Category'] == category]  # elif a unique category is selected, return unique items
        item_options = get_items_in_category(category)  # item_options updates to unique items for that category
    sel_item.options = item_options # then passes item_options as options for sel_item variable  
    
    #------------------------Filter For size slider ---------------------------#

    if (category != 'All') & (size == sel_size.value):
        category_filter = mac[(mac['Category'] == category) 
                              & (mac['Serving Size (g)'] <= size)].sort_values(by = 'Serving Size (g)', ascending = False)

    if (category == 'All') & (item == 'All') & (size == sel_size.value):
        category_filter = mac[(mac['Serving Size (g)'] <= size)].sort_values(by = 'Serving Size (g)', ascending = False)

    #------------------------Filter For selected item type---------------------------#
    
    if item == 'All':
        pass # do nothing
    else:
        category_filter = mac[(mac['Category'] == category) & (mac['Item'] == item)] # else All category & items
        
    #-------------------Filter For selected nutrient type---------------------#
    
    if nutrient == 'All':
        pass # do nothing
    elif nutrient == sel_nutrient.value: # if a nutrient is selected
        sort_filter = sort_by(mac2, sel_nutrient.value) # sort by nutrient in dataframe(mac2)
        category_filter = sort_filter[sort_filter['Category'] == category] # output
       
    # if a category & value is All & nutrient is selected, sort by nutrient in dataframe(mac2)
    if (category == 'All') & (nutrient == sel_nutrient.value) & (value == 'All'):
        category_filter = sort_by(mac2, sel_nutrient.value) # output
        
    #--------------------Filter For selected % daily value type--------------------#
        
    if value == 'All':
        pass # do nothing
    elif value == sel_value.value: # if a value is selected

    with nutrients_output:
        print('There are', len(category_filter), 'Items in this category' ) # prints output details
        display(category_filter) # displays Output
    
    with nutrients_plot:
        plt.figure(figsize=(15,10)) # set figure size for graph
        global compare_filter # makes variable a global one
        
        if (plot == 'All'):
            pass # do nothing
        
        elif (category != 'All') & (item != 'All') & (plot == 'Compare Nutrients'):
            compare_filter = mac4[(mac4['Category'] == category) & (mac4['Item'] == item)]
            
            print('This Shows Nutrient Stats For ', item) # prints graph details  
            print('Sodium isn\'t included due to its ridiculuous high amount in Food Items on the menu ') # prints graph details  
            
            # ---- plot a pointplot chart ---- #
            sns.pointplot(data = compare_filter, color = 'r' ) # Gets output from category_filter variable
            plt.xticks(rotation = 90, fontsize = 15) # set x axis ticks format
            plt.xlabel('Nutrients', fontsize = 15) # set x axis label
            plt.yticks(fontsize = 15) # set y axis ticks format
            
            # --- To edit the Legend --- # 
            legend_labels = [item] # set legend to values in item
            handles = [plt.Line2D([], [], color = 'r', marker = '.', markersize = 10, linewidth = 2)]
            plt.legend(handles = handles, labels = legend_labels, loc = 1 , fontsize = 20)

            plt.grid() # type of plot
            plt.show()
            
        elif (category != 'All') & (item != 'All') & (plot == 'Compare % Daily value'):
            compare_filter = mac5[(mac5['Category'] == category) & (mac5['Item'] == item)]
            
            print('This Shows % Daily value Stats For ', item) # prints graph details  
            # ---- plot a pointplot chart ---- #
            sns.pointplot(data = compare_filter, color = 'g' ) # Gets output from category_filter variable
            plt.xticks(rotation = 90, fontsize = 15) # set x axis ticks format
            plt.xlabel('Nutrients', fontsize = 15) # set x axis label
            plt.yticks(fontsize = 15) # set y axis ticks format

About Data Exploration & Visuals:

* With this Dashboards you can select a Food category.
* With the category selected, you can select a Food item in that category, to view nutrient or % Daily value stats      individually.
* With a category selected, you can sort with the Serving size slider. When other dropdowns are set to All, aside that  Serving size slider is normally disabled.
* After selecting a Category, you can either sort by Nutrients or % Daily value (but not both) to sort the output from  in descending order according to the Nutrient or % Daily value selected.
* View your data by selecting the Plots tab.

Notes For Dashboard use:

* Select Category.
* Sort by Serving size - `slider only activates when a category is selected & other dropdowns are set to All.
* Sort by Nutreints when a Category is selected, to view the output in descending order by Nutrient selected         
(Sort % Daily value must be set to All if activated).
* Sort by % Daily value when a Category is selected, to view the output in descending order by value selected 
(Sort Nutrients must be set to All if activated).
* After Sorting, view plots in Plot tab by either Nutrients or % Daily value.
